

--VARIABLES--
   > Containers that hold information, purpose is to label and store data in the computer's memory

--Initilization (Declaration & Assignment)--
   > Once initilizing a variable, that variable will furthermore evaluate to the value assigned
         ex. let bootcamp = "App Academy"
            console.log(bootcamp) => prints "App Academy"

   > "let" and "=" used to assign values to variables

~Javascript variable names can contain any alphanumeric character; "_" or "$", HOWEVER, cannot begin w/ a number~

--Manipulating Variables--
> Using basic operands will not reassign the value of a variable. Must use shorthand operations.

*Shorthand Variable Operands*

+= ... adds to a number and reassigns value
-= ... subtracts from a number and reassigns value
/= ... divides number and reassigns value
*= ... multiplies number and reassigns value

(++) and (--) add or subtract a number by exactly 1


--DATA TYPES--

--String
>represents textual data, must be encapsulated by '' or ""
  ex. "hello!"  "hello world"

  *Important String Methods*
   .charAt()- returns character at specified offset
   .concat()- appends a string to another, returns new string
   .indexOf()- returns index at the first occurance of specified substring
   .lastIndexOf()- returns index at the last occurance of specified substring
   .match()- retrieves result of matching a string against a regular expression
   .replace()- searches a string for a value, returns new string w/ values replaced
   .slice()- extracts part of a string, returns in new string, not changing original
   .includes()- returns true if a string contains specified value, false if not found (also Array method)
   .split()- splits a string into an array of substrings, does not change orginal string
   .endsWith()- determines whether a string ends w/ specified characters, returning 'true' or 'false'

--Number
> an integer or floating number point- can also be +Infinity, -Infinity
  ex. 3, 3.5, 3e-2

--Boolean
>represents logical entities, true or false, like a yes/no switch

--Object
>complex data type that allows for storing of collections of data.  Array is technically considered a special type of object.

--Arrays
>an ordered list, each item in an array is called an element, index starts at 0
>arrays can hold any data type
>can be indexed using []

 *Important Array Methods*
   .push()- adds one or more elements to the end of an array and returns new length
   .pop()- removes last element from array, returns that element changing length of array
   .shift()- removes first element from an array, returns removed element changing length
   .unshift()- adds one or more elements to the beginning of an array and returns new length
   .splice()- add or remove elements from an array, changes array
   .slice()- copies part of an array and returns that copied part as new array, not modifiying original array
   .join()- returns an array as a string, does not change original array
   Array.isArray()- determines whether passed in value is an array 

--NaN
> A nonsensical arithmetic will result in NaN
  ex. let num;
       console.log(num + 3) = NaN

--Null
> represents intentional absence of any object value, not same as undefined

--Undefined
>represents a value that is not assigned.  If a variable is declared but the value is not assigned, that value will = undefined.

--typeof (operator)
>to find out the type of a variable, 'typeof' operator may be used
   ex. let name= "Athena"
       typeof(name) => "string"
